ets rallied hard (**BTC +6.66%, ETH +6.96%**).\n- **TSLA (+0.39%)** gained despite extreme P/E of 375.7\u2014suggests momentum-driven buying regardless of valuation.\n\n## Key Metrics & Concerns\n\n**Valuation Red Flags:**\n- **PLTR (P/E 240.7), TSLA (375.7), AMD (76.2), AVGO (65.9)** all trade at extremely elevated multiples, vulnerable to sentiment shifts.\n- **QQQ's P/E of 32.9** vs. **SPY's 26.6** reinforces concentration risk in mega-cap tech.\n\n**Encouragement:**\n- **Dividend stocks remain attractive**: **VZ (558%), T (409%), CVX (371%)** offer significant yield, though quality varies.\n- **Energy's relative strength** and **XLE's 262% dividend** suggest the market is pricing in structural commodity demand.\n\n## Themes to Watch\n\n1. **Interest Rate Trajectory** \u2014 Financial sector weakness (XLF -3.05%) may signal rising rate expectations; monitor Fed communications closely.\n\n2. **Crypto Momentum** \u2014 Strong weekly gains across digital assets (+6-8%) could indicate renewed institutional appetite or macro catalyst (e.g., regulatory clarity).\n\n3. **Earnings Season** \u2014 High P/E valuations (especially tech) demand strong execution. NFLX's decline warrants scrutiny.\n\n4. **Energy Supply Dynamics** \u2014 XLE's outperformance suggests geopolitical risk pricing; monitor global supply developments.\n\n5. **Sector Rotation** \u2014 Defensive underperformance (healthcare, staples) combined with energy/tech outperformance hints at cautious risk-on positioning rather than full risk-off.\n\n---\n\n**Forecast**: Expect continued consolidation with sector-specific drivers dominating headline risk. Monitor credit spreads and rate expectations for next week's directional signal.",
